Anonymous Wed 15 Nov 2023 23:15:18 No.61147099 Report
Quoted By: >>61147573 >>61147665
>>61146920
I respect your dedication to the craft of writing. But you are overthinking this. The audience are going to hear the German accent and say "wuh? is she German?" If you want her manner of speech to convey to a wide audience that she is from Ye Olden Tymes and from the British Isles, try a current rural English accent, like Devonshire. Look for colorful regional phrases for her to use. Don't go overboard with Thuh Fun-et-ick Spellins, as they are distracting and annoying after their first appearance.

Anonymous Thu 16 Nov 2023 00:04:38 No.61148212 Report
Quoted By: >>61148485
>>61147573
>Would that be too much?
NTA, but yes to the power of ten. If you intend for this story to be read by people other than you, I encourage you to reconsider jamming in a fuckload of different accents, speaking styles, or straight up dialects. That's very similar to rapidly hitting readers with a bunch of made up magic or scifi technobabble right away. You have to spread new concepts and ways of thinking out or you'll overload a reader, because even if you know what is intended it's your job as the writer to convey that smoothly for the audience.
There is a reason almost every published novel finds ways to skip past language or dialect barriers. It's fucking awful to read. If someone sees a summary about a pagan deer but goes to read it but the first chapter's dialogue is frontloaded gobbedygook of phonetic accents and dialects from every other character, or worse every time new groups are introduce this happens, you cannot reasonably expect readers to stick around. The rare exceptions to this but, I could be wrong, it doesn't sound like you plan to do any of them.
